just_use auto_player.py

# label: EARLY (auto-player)
# role: agent tool — drives a LynRummy session via Python-native hints

Fetches state, calls `hints.build_suggestions(hand, board)`
locally, takes the top suggestion's primitives and posts each
verbatim to `/actions`. No /hint round-trip, no trick_result
on the wire — every action is a primitive.

Emission is correct-by-construction: `hints.py` runs a
`_fix_geometry` post-pass at the end of each trick so the
primitive sequence lands on a geometrically clean board. No
settle() belt. Terminates when the deck drops below
DECK_LOW_WATER (≈10 cards) — not on "victory" events, which
are per-turn bonuses (see
`project_lynrummy_game_end_condition.md`).

## Surface

- `python3 games/lynrummy/python/auto_player.py` — fresh session.
- `--session N` — resume an existing session.
- `--max-actions N` — safety cap (default 200).

## Pointers

- Depends on: `client.py`, `hints.py`, `geometry.py` (all same dir),
  `/actions` + `/state` + `/score` endpoints in
  `views/lynrummy_elm.go`.
- Hints architecture: client-side per `project_hints_are_client_side.md`.
  Go owns wire + referee; Python owns decomposition.

## TODO

- Synthesis covers `move_stack` today via `gesture_synth`;
  hand-origin primitives (`merge_hand`, `place_hand`) and
  `split` / `merge_stack` still teleport in replay because
  `drag_endpoints` honestly returns None when Python doesn't
  know both endpoints. Elm's async DOM-measurement pipeline
  covers hand-origin synthesis at replay time; intra-board
  ones are a candidate for widening `gesture_synth`.
